Even though we are focused on categorical inputs in this example, we should always fit an INTERCEPT-ONLY or constant average model first.

Next, let's fit the model that ONLY includes the categorical input!

This model has one and only one input.

Last week, when we fit a linear model with a single input linearly related to the (average) output, there were 2 coefficients estimated. The intercept and the slope multiplying the input.

Let's see what happens we use a model with a single categorical input.

In [21]:
def my_coefplot(mod, figsize_use=(10,4)):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize_use)
    
    ax.errorbar(y =mod.params.index,
                x =mod.params,
                xerr = 2 * mod.bse,
                fmt='o', color='k', ecolor='k', elinewidth=2, ms=10)
    
    ax.axvline(x=0, linestyle='--', color='grey', linewidth=3.5)
    
    ax.set_xlabel('coefficient value')
    
    plt.show()
In [22]:
my_coefplot( fit_A_1 )

But why are there 3 coefficients even though there is 1 and only 1 input????

The reason is because the input is CATEGORICAL and has 3 categories!!!

Let's begin understanding how the categorical input "works" by examining predictions.

Let's use the TRAINING SET predictions first. The TRAINING SET predictions are called the FITS or FITTEDVALUES.

Dummies are BINARY indicators. A value of 0 means that Dummy's category is NOT present while a value of 1 means that Dummy's category is present for a row in the data.

If all DUMMIES equal 0 for a ROW, then the input equals the REFERENCE category!!!!

Dummy variables require a REFERENCE POINT to be identified. By default, that reference point is the first category alphabetically.

This means, the number of features derived from a categorical input EQUALS the number of categories minus 1.

Even though the input is NON-NUMERIC behind the scenes numeric (integer) features are derived. The derived dummy variables are either 0 or 1.

This means making predictions works the same way as with numeric inputs!

The coefficients multiply the features and their products are summed!!!!!!!

Let's see how the coefficients and features are used to make the predictions.

Categorical inputs therefore cause the INTERCEPT to have a real meaning. The INTERCEPT equals the AVERAGE OUTPUT at the reference category!!!!

The dummy variable coefficients also have an important physical meaning. We add the dummy coefficients to the intercept. The dummy coefficients are therefore the RELATIVE effect from the REFERENCE!!!!!

Statistical significance for dummy coefficients therefore means are we confident the category has an effect relative to the reference!!

Working with linear models with Mixed Inputs¶

General workflow:

  • Fit an INTERCEPT-ONLY linear model
  • Fit a model with ONLY the categorical inputs
  • Fit a model with ONLY the linear additive continuous inputs
  • Fit models with MIXED INPUTS - categorical and continuous inputs

The previous recording already fit the INTERCEPT-ONLY and the categorical only models. So let's fit the continuous only model.

In [62]:
fit_A_1c = smf.ols(formula='y ~ x1', data=dfA1).fit()

Mixed Input models¶

We have the same set of choices with mixed inputs as we do with multiple numeric inputs. Meaning, we must decide if we want ADDITIVE vs INTERACTION features!!!!

The INTERCEPT in general is the AVERAGE OUTPUT given ALL FEATURES equaling ZERO!!!!

When we have mixed inputs, that corresponds to the categorical input equaling the REFERENCE category and the continuous inputs equaling zero.

Predictions will help visualize the TRENDS so we can examine what happens ACROSS the categories!!!

We will NOT look at the TRAINING SET fits! Instead, we will make predictions on NEW data!

The new data MUST include all inputs used in the model!!!!!

Since we have just 2 inputs, let's consider MANY unique values between the TRAINING SET min/max for the continuous input and ALL categories for the categorical input.

Visualize prediction uncertainty¶

The predictive trends are important but they are NOT the full story! We also need to communicate the uncertainty on the average (CONFIDENCE INTERVAL) and the uncertainty on a single observation or measurement (PREDICTION INTERVAL).

Last week, we saw how to do that with the .get_prediction().summary_frame() methods. However, we only had a single continuous input and so we need to see how to handle the situation when we allow MULTIPLE inputs to vary!!!!!

Everything you are about to see works when there are 2 inputs with varying values in the prediction grid!

for i, a_x2 in enumerate( the_x2_values ):
    # filter the data to a single category
    df_for_subplot = pred_viz_summary_5_combine.loc[ pred_viz_summary_5_combine.x2 == a_x2, : ].copy()
    
    # prediction interval
    ax[i].fill_between( df_for_subplot.x1,
                        df_for_subplot.obs_ci_lower, df_for_subplot.obs_ci_upper,
                        facecolor='orange', edgecolor='orange' )
    
    # confidence interval
    ax[i].fill_between( df_for_subplot.x1,
                        df_for_subplot.mean_ci_lower, df_for_subplot.mean_ci_upper, 
                        facecolor='grey', edgecolor='grey')
    
    # trend
    ax[i].plot(df_for_subplot.x1, df_for_subplot['mean'], color='black')
    
    # set labels
    ax[i].set_xlabel('x1')
    ax[i].set_ylabel('y')
    ax[i].set_title('x2: %s' % a_x2)
    
# show the plot

Dummies vs Onehots¶

The dummy variables derived from the categorical input are one way to DERIVE features from categorical inputs.

One hot encodings or "onehots" are an alternative approach. They share certain similarities but the interpretations are different.

In [141]:
XA1_df_1.head()
Out[141]:
Intercept x2[T.A2] x2[T.A3] intercept_product dummy2_product dummy3_product model_pred
0 1.0 0.0 1.0 -1.339974 0.000000 1.372002 0.032028
1 1.0 0.0 0.0 -1.339974 0.000000 0.000000 -1.339974
2 1.0 1.0 0.0 -1.339974 2.469504 0.000000 1.129530
3 1.0 1.0 0.0 -1.339974 2.469504 0.000000 1.129530
4 1.0 0.0 1.0 -1.339974 0.000000 1.372002 0.032028

Let's first create the ONEHOTS and examine them inside their design matrix and then consider their coefficients from their model.

By default the formula interface works with DUMMY variables. We can force ONE HOTS by "removing the intercept". You can "remove" or not-select a variable within the formula interface via the - operator.

In [142]:
yA1_df_1onehot, XA1_df_1onehot = dmatrices('y ~ x2 - 1', data=dfA1, return_type='dataframe')

4 0.0 0.0 1.0

The one-hot encodings REMOVE the intercept feature and replace it with the reference category!

In [152]:

You must be VERY careful with coefficient interpretation especially statistically significance when using ONE HOT ENCODINGS!!!!

The one hot encoding p-values just tell you if you are confident in the SIGN of the average output for each category!!!!

To use the p-value, "as it is", we are really supposed to consider RELATIVE changes!!!!!

my_coefplot( fit_A_1 )
